!TITLE
COBWEBS IN THE CHURCH
!WORDS
An artist was asked to paint a picture of a decaying church.  To the 
amazement of many, instead of depicting on canvas a tottering old 
building, he portrayed a stately edifice of modern design.  Through 
the open portals could be seen a richly carved pulpit, a magnificent 
organ and beautiful stained-glass windows. In the vestibule was a 
large offering plate for the gifts of fashionable worshipers.  But 
that's where the artist's idea of a decaying church became obvious. 
Next to this plate hung a small coinbox bearing an inscription that 
read, "For Missions." Over the slot through which contributions could 
be dropped he had painted a huge cobweb!
  Any church that is not involved in proclaiming the gospel to the 
world should take another look at its priorities.  It may have an 
imposing structure and a large budget, and the congregation may be 
engaged in feverish activity.  But if God's missionary program for 
this age goes unaided or unattended, something is drastically wrong.
