!TITLE
BLINDSIDED BY GOD
!WORDS
 Sherwood Wirt writes:  "In August, 1954, John Landy of Australia was 
pitted against Roger Bannister of Britain in what was called 
the'Miracle Mile.'  Both men had broken the four- minute mile that 
year with world record performances, and had been the first to do 
so.  On this dramatic occasion they were brought together to compete 
directly with each other at the British Empire Games in Vancouver, 
British Columbia.
    "While the world watched, the two men came around the curve on 
the final lap of the mile run with Landy in the lead.  He turned his 
head to the left for an instant, whereupon Bannister with a burst of 
speed passed him on the right, then held on to the tape.  Bannister's 
winning time was 3:58.8.
    "That race could be considered an analogy of God's dealings with 
His children.  He loves to blindside us, to come up behind us and 
pass us when we're not aware he is anywhere around.  That is part of 
His joy.  You have experienced this same thing yourself.  You helped 
somebody push his car, you put in a good word, wrote a letter, looked 
up something, made a telephone call for somebody else, plugged a leak 
in a neighbor's kitchen, fixed a child's toy, returned good for 
evil.  It's nothing particularly religious; you just did it because 
you felt like doing it.
    "A year later you received a thank-you, a surprise call, perhaps 
an unexpected invitation, a job offer, or even a check, and you 
recognized that God was in it all the time, working out the promises 
of His Word in His own way and according to His own plan.  He just 
likes to pass us on the right when our heads are turned to the left, 
and breezes on to victory."
   [World, Feb 19, 1994.  Page 26.]
